review_comments.body:
As it turns out,  its a mistake in how I was running my tests. When you
carefully and correctly define the schema in pig, the loaders are correct.

However, applying ProtobufBytesToTuple directly as a function in pig instead
of through a loader will not work without this section. Given its lack of
usefulness outside of a loader, this is a limitation that is plenty
acceptable, so I'm going to revert it.

Scott
 On Aug 17, 2011 9:29 PM, "rangadi" <
reply@reply.github.com>
wrote:

> > @@ -54,9 +53,23 @@ public class ProtobufBytesToTuple<M extends Message>
> > extends EvalFunc<Tuple> {
> > return null;
> > }
> > try {
> > - DataByteArray bytes = (DataByteArray) input.get(0);
> > - M value_ = protoConverter_.fromBytes(bytes.get());
> > - return new ProtobufTuple(value_);
> > - Object o = input.get(0);
> > - if(o instanceof DataByteArray){
> > - DataByteArray bytes = (DataByteArray) input.get(0);
> > - M value_ = protoConverter_.fromBytes(bytes.get());
> > - return new ProtobufTuple(value_);
> > - }
> > - else if(o instanceof DataBag){
> > - Iterator<Tuple> tupleIterator = ((DataBag) o).iterator();
> > - DataBag bag = new DefaultDataBag();
> 
> What is the intention here? In the case of a DataBag, it returns a tuple
> with the bag. Did you forget invoking ProtobufTuple()?
> 
> ## 
> 
> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub:
> https://github.com/kevinweil/elephant-bird/pull/71/files#r95478

